e.g

```rust

let s = String::from("hello"); // ownership exist in throughout this scope

{
 let g = String::from("hello1"); // ownerhsip only exist in this scope
}

let s1 = s;  //ownership now exist in s1 and s is discard

//hence this should output error

println!("print x: {}", s); //output error s does not exist
```

`s1` takes ownership from `s`  i.e moved from `s` to `s1` because rust does shallow copy. and it is bad if memory is free twice and also having two variable pointing to thesame data on the heap. hence `s` needs to be invalid so we only have a single pointer and memory is freed once.

to do deep copy manually we can use `clone`

```rust

let s1 = String::from("hello");
let s2 = s1.clone();

println!("s1= {}, s2 = {}", s1, s2);
  ```

also when variable pointing to data on a heap is passed to a function, that function tkaes the ownership

```rust

let s - String::from("hello");

takes_ownership(s);

println!("s: {}", s); // should output error


fn takes_ownership(s: String) {
println!("s {}", s);
}
```

To prevent a function from taking over the ownership from outter scope

```rust

fn main() {

  let mut s = String::from("hello");

change(&mut s) //pass a reference to the function

//s is still valid here

}


fn change(s: &mut String) {
  s.push_str(", world");
}
```

* One of the law of reference and borrowing is that you can't have more than one mutable reference

```rust
    let mut s = String::from("hello");

    let r1 = &mut s;
    let r2 = &mut s;

    println!("{}, {}", r1, r2); //error

```

You can't have immutable reference and mutable reference.

```rust
    let mut s = String::from("hello");

    let r1 = &s; // no problem
    let r2 = &s; // no problem
    let r3 = &mut s; // BIG PROBLEM

    println!("{}, {}, and {}", r1, r2, r3);

```

since at compile time, the last use of the muttable reference is tracked, you can make use of the mutable after the last use e.g

```rust
    let mut s = String::from("hello");

    let r1 = &s; // no problem
    let r2 = &s; // no problem
    println!("{} and {}", r1, r2);
    // variables r1 and r2 will not be used after this point

    let r3 = &mut s; // no problem
    println!("{}", r3);


```
## Dangling reference

``` rust
fn dangling() -> &String {
 let s = String::from("hello");

&s
}

// this one will create a dangling pointer, since s will be out of scope once function is returned.
```

to prevent dangling reference

```rust

fn non_dangling() -> String {
   let s = String::from("hello");
   s
}
```

```rust
fn main() {
    let mut s = String::from("hello world");

    let word = first_word(&s);

    s.clear(); // error!

    println!("the first word is: {}", word);
}

```
Indexing `s` with word won't be valid. `s` since s is already out of scope


but if we use slicing we can detect this error properly

```rust
fn first_word(s: &String) -> &str {
    let bytes = s.as_bytes();

    for (i, &item) in bytes.iter().enumerate() {
        if item == b' ' {
            return &s[0..i];
        }
    }

    &s[..]
}

fn main() {
    let mut s = String::from("hello world");

    let word = first_word(&s);

    s.clear(); // error!

    println!("the first word is: {}", word);
}
```

doing the println scope `word` is not valid cause the reference is conterminated; we have immutable and muttable reference from passing to function `first_word` and `clear`

